      "text": "ISO-NE PUBLIC\nS E P T E M B E R 1 7 T H | P A C W E B E X\nBen Wilson, Ellinor Ross, & Richard Kornitsky\nE C O N O M I C S T U D I E S & E N V I R O N M E N T A L O U T L O O K\nSystem Efficiency Needs Scenario – Results\n2024 Economic Study\nISO-NE PUBLIC 2\nOverview of Presentation\n• Overview of the 2024 Economic Study\n• Overview of Methodology\n• First Pass Results\n• Second Pass Results\n• Generic Upgrades\n• Next Steps\nOVERVIEW OF THE ECONOMIC STUDY\n\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nObjective of the Economic Study Process\n• Provide information to stakeholders to facilitate \nthe evaluation of economic and environmental \nimpacts of New England regional policies, \nfederal policies, and various resource \ntechnologies on satisfying future resource needs \nin the region\n– Identify system efficiency issues on the PTF portion \nof the New England Transmission System and, as \napplicable, evaluate competitive solutions to \nalleviate identified system efficiency needs\n• The 2024 Economic Study is anticipated to \nconclude by December 2025\n4\nISO-NE PUBLIC 5\nEconomic Study Reference Scenarios\n✓ Benchmark Scenario – Model previous calendar year and compare it to historical \nsystem performance. This scenario’s purpose is to test the fidelity of models against \nhistorical performance and improve the models for future scenarios\nPolicy Scenario – Model future years (>10-year planning horizon) based on \nsatisfying New England region and other energy policies and goals\nSystem Efficiency Needs Scenario (SENS) – Model future year (10-year planning \nhorizon) based on the ISO’s existing planning criteria to identify system efficiency \nissues that could meet the threshold for a system efficiency Needs Assessment \nwhich could result in a competitive solution process for System Efficiency \nTransmission Upgrades needs\nStakeholder-Requested Scenario – Scenario with a region-wide scope that is \nrequested by stakeholders and not covered by the other 3 scenarios or potential \nsensitivities on those 3 scenarios\nISO-NE PUBLIC 6\nEconomic Studies Technical Guide\n• The ISO published the first version of the \nEconomic Studies Technical Guide (ESTG) on \nMarch 25, 2024\n– Revision 1.1 of the ESTG was released on\nAugust 5, 2025 \n– Appendix C: System Efficiency Needs Scenario\nprovides additional detail on the SENS \n• The ESTG seeks to provide stakeholders, \npolicy makers, and the public with a \ncomprehensive document that describes the \nEconomic Study process\n– The goal is to provide increased accessibility and \nunderstanding of the Economic Studies\nMETHODOLOGY OVERVIEW\n\nISO-NE PUBLIC 8\nPurpose of System Efficiency Needs Scenario\n• The System Efficiency Needs Scenario (SENS) is a method to \nidentify future congestion needs on the New England PTF \nsystem and evaluate potential solutions to the identified \ncongestion\n• The ISO presented assumptions at the August Planning \nAdvisory Committee \n• To identify potential system efficiency needs, the ISO utilizes \na two-pass production cost model\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nMethodology Overview\n• Because the ISO is focused on New England centric metrics, the \ninterregional SENS model will be run differently than other ISO \nproduction cost models \n• An initial 2035 interregional model will be run with only interregional \ntransfer limits enforced. This will show the economic transfers regardless \nof internal transmission constraints\n• Then, a second pass will be run with the import/export profiles and LMPs \nof the first pass used on a New England-only model\n• In the second pass, the optimized quantities within the model will be the \ncost of the New England energy supply, consisting of:\n– Production cost of New England generators\n– Marginal prices of imports from other regions \n9\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nMethodology Overview, cont.\n• In the second pass model, congestion within New England will be \nflagged by the model and require a redispatch \n– The model will calculate the hours that a constraint is binding and the \nshadow price ($/MWh differential) across the binding constraint\n• After running the second pass, the ISO will extract all binding \nconstraints and multiply the two quantities (hours binding and \nshadow price) to produce a congestion magnitude \n– This way, the ISO can rank the worst congestion points based on \nfrequency and expected cost\n• Generic upgrades will then be modeled for the three worst \ncongestion points and production cost savings will be recorded\n– The ISO will also note if congestion shifts to other elements\n10\nFIRST PASS RESULTS\n\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nFirst Pass Overview – Import Modeling\n• In the first pass of the model, only interregional transmission \nconstraints are enforced. This is done to avoid “pre-curtailing” \nimports that could contribute towards New England congestion in \nthe second pass\n• This section will show the projected flows across interregional \nlines connected to ISO-NE\n• The forecasting information provided by external areas has a \nmeaningful effect on results\n– Future import and export patterns are significantly different from recent \nhistorical patterns, especially with HQ and New Brunswick\n• New England exports more energy than in recent years\n12\nISO-NE PUBLIC 13\nForecast Submitted by HQ\n• Historically, HQ has been a net exporter to other regions due to an \nexcess of available energy. From 2019-2023:\n– Demand has averaged 188 TWh \n– Generation has averaged 203 TWh from Hydro, 11 TWh from wind, and 5 TWh \nfrom biomass/fossil resources\n– This has led to an average net export of 31 TWh to other NPCC regions\n• Based on the NERC LTRA forecast data submitted by HQ, the \nsupply/demand balance will shift by 2035:\n– Demand will increase to 248 TWh\n– New certain generation includes ~4 GW of wind, leading to another 11 TWh of \ngeneration\n– The forecast submitted by HQ includes more load growth than generation \nadditions in Quebec\n• The net energy budget for exports is projected to change from +31 TWh to -17 TWh\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nInterregional Net Imports & Exports\n• *Note: a negative value indicates a net importer (into the region), while a positive value \nindicates a net exporter (out of the region) \n• The net exporting systems are IESO and the PJM representation, while all other areas \nare net importers\n• Annual flows on individual interregional lines can be found in Appendix 1\n14\nArea HQ IESO MT NYISO PJM ISONE\nLoad (GWh) 247,417 187,017 30,520 173,829 0 144,712\nGeneration \n(GWh) 233,254 207,023 27,741 171,097 9,861 135,883\nNet Import/ \nExport* \n(GWh)\n-14,163 20,006 -2,779 -2,733 9,861 -8,829\nISO-NE PUBLIC\n2035 Interregional Flows: NY - NE\n• New England is a net importer from New York, importing 11.2 TWh of energy\n• New England is a net exporter to New York during the summer peak period\n15\n-2000\n-1500\n-1000\n-500\n0\n500\n1000\n1500\n2000\nMW\nChronological Duration\n<--------- Out of NE | Into NE -------->\nISO-NE PUBLIC\n2035 Interregional Flows: HQ - NE\n• New England is a net importer from Quebec, but net imports are much lower than \nhistorical imports (1.3 TWh)\n• New England is frequently exporting to Quebec during the spring and fall, and \nimporting from Quebec in the summer and winter peak periods \n16\n-2000\n-1500\n-1000\n-500\n0\n500\n1000\n1500\n2000\n2500\n3000\n3500\nMW\n<\nChronological Duration --------- Out of NE | Into NE -------->\nISO-NE PUBLIC\n2035 Interregional Flows: NB - NE\n• New England is a net exporter to New Brunswick, exporting 3.7 TWh\n• New England is importing from New Brunswick during the winter peak \nperiods \n17\n<--------- Out of NE | Into NE -------->\n-800\n-600\n-400\n-200\n0\n200\n400\n600\n800\n1000\n1200\nMW\nChronological Duration\nISO-NE PUBLIC\n2035 Interregional Flows: NB+HQ - NE\n• New England is a net exporter to Canada, sending 2.4 TWh of net energy \nnorth\n• However, New England is a net importer from Canada during the winter and \nsummer months\n