      "title": "How are transmission congestion revenues distributed? - Ask ISO",
      "published_date": "2024-09-30T00:00:00.000Z",
      "text": "How are transmission congestion revenues distributed?\n\nLoading\n\n## Sep 30, 2024Knowledge\n\n### Information\n\nTitle\n\nHow are transmission congestion revenues distributed?\n\nContent\n\nIn short, the ISO determines how much congestion revenue there is to allocate which is based on the congestion revenue collected from the Day-Ahead and Real-Time Locational Marginal Prices, and also includes any negative FTR Target Allocations. If there is sufficient revenue to compensate all of the FTR Target Allocations, then the FTR Holders are credited.\n\nSection 6 of M-06 describes the transmission congestion accounting. As the Operating Days are settled, the ISO collects Transmission Congestion Revenue by summing all Market Participants ’Day-Ahead Energy Market Congestion Charges/Credits and all Market Participants’ and Transmission Customers’ Real-Time Energy Market Deviation CongestionCharges/Credits for the month.\n\nEach FTR holder gets a Target Allocation for their FTR based on the difference between the congestion components of the locational marginal prices (LMPs) of two pricing nodes of an FTR (i.e., the source and sink locations of a given FTR) in the Day-Ahead Energy Market. If a target allocation is negative (an obligation to pay), that is added to the total congestion revenue.\n\nThe total positive Target Allocations are compensated if there are sufficient Transmission Congestion Revenues in a month. At the end of the calendar year, any excess monthly Transmission Congestion Revenue is distributed first to FTR Holders that were paid less than their positive Target FTR Allocations and then pro-rata to Market Participants who paid Congestion Costs during the year.\n\nThe Congestion Revenue Summary includes the pool totals for the distribution of transmission congestion revenues.\n\nNote that the transmission congestion revenue distribution is a separate settlement than the FTR Auction Revenues which are allocated to those with Auction Revenue Rights (ARRs). See the How are FTR Auction Revenues Distributed article for more details on that.\n\nLast Modified Date\n\n9/30/2024 2:15 PM\n\nURL Name\n\nHow-are-transmission-congestion-revenues-distributed\n\nFinancial Transmission Rights (FTR) & Auction Revenue Rights (ARR) Markets\n\nDrop Files\n\nUpload FilesOr drop files\n\n## Trending Articles\n\n- How to pick-up a digital certificate\n- How to import (install) a digital certificate to use in Chrome or Edge\n- Non-Commercial Continuous Storage Facility (CSF) Assets Offering in eMarket as a Generator DARD and ATRR\n- What MIS reports should be viewed when the bill line item for OATT Schedule 2 VAR does not agree with the values on the OA…\n- What is regional network service?\n\nLoading\n\nHow are transmission congestion revenues distributed?",
      "highlights": [
        "In short, the ISO determines how much congestion revenue there is to allocate which is based on the congestion revenue collected from the Day-Ahead and Real-Time Locational Marginal Prices, and also includes any negative FTR Target Allocations. If there is sufficient revenue to compensate all of the FTR Target Allocations, then the FTR Holders are credited.\n[...]\nSection 6 of M-06 describes the transmission congestion accounting. As the Operating Days are settled, the ISO collects Transmission Congestion Revenue by summing all Market Participants ’Day-Ahead Energy Market Congestion Charges/Credits and all Market Participants’ and Transmission Customers’ Real-Time Energy Market Deviation CongestionCharges/Credits for the month.\n[...]\nEach FTR holder gets a Target Allocation for their FTR based on the difference between the congestion components of the locational marginal prices (LMPs) of two pricing nodes of an FTR (i.e., the source and sink locations of a given FTR) in the Day-Ahead Energy Market. If a target allocation is negative (an obligation to pay), that is added to the total congestion revenue.\n[...]\nThe total positive Target Allocations are compensated if there are sufficient Transmission Congestion Revenues in a month. At the end of the calendar year, any excess monthly Transmission Congestion Revenue is distributed first to FTR Holders that were paid less than their positive Target FTR Allocations and then pro-rata to Market Participants who paid Congestion Costs during the year.\n[...]\nThe Congestion Revenue Summary includes the pool totals for the distribution of transmission congestion revenues.\n[...]\nNote that the transmission congestion revenue distribution is a separate settlement than the FTR Auction Revenues which are allocated to those with Auction Revenue Rights (ARRs). See the How are FTR Auction Revenues Distributed article for more details on that."
