      "text": "2023 Historical Hourly Flows and Limits – New England Transmission \nInterfaces \nBackground \nWithin ISO New England’s Energy Management System (EMS), the Interface Limits Calculator (ILC) program provides a high \nlevel security overview of MW flows on the ISO New England Bulk Electric System (BES). ILC presents the flows and \ncalculated/implied limit across pre-defined interfaces, which are lines and transformers that are grouped together and \nmonitored as a subset of the power system. An interface limit is the maximum flow permitted across an interface without \nexceeding a thermal, stability, or voltage limit for that interface. Some interfaces are intuitive, such as borders with other \nControl Areas (e.g., New England-New York and New England-New Brunswick). Others are less intuitive and are often the \nresult of engineering studies as the system has evolved and expanded (North-South, New Hampshire-Maine, etc.). \nIn order to ensure the effective and reliable transfer of electricity on the New England Electric Grid and prevent reliability \nviolations, system operators will use Transmission Operating Guides, and their expertise to limit interface flow and activate \nconstraints when required. These constraints, when binding, will result in congestion pricing within LMPs, and will keep the \nflow below the interface limit. \nThis year, a summarization of the actual MW flows and limits during the calendar year 2023 on thirty-five (39) of the major \nthermal, stability, and voltage interfaces monitored by ISO New England has been performed. \nMethod \nILC data (actual flow and interface limit) were sampled on the half-hour for each of the 39 interfaces for the calendar year. \nAs discussed in the next section, certain assumptions have been made and reflected in the data. Then, summary statistics \nwere calculated on the hourly values, and monthly summaries of the valid hourly values are presented in the spreadsheet \nentitled ‘2023 Flows and Limits Summary Statistics' spreadsheet posted here. \nAbout These Data \nDue to limitations in the design of the ILC application, there are many conditions in which, due to operational conditions or \ndirection of flow, the hourly limits are assigned a default computational value that is unrelated to any limit. Beginning with \nthe 2017 edition of this report, these default values have been removed. When this data was included in the previous \nreports, it skewed the analytics performed on these data. All limit values that appear missing in the ‘Hourly Flows and \nLimits’ reports signify a default value occurred in that interval. Summary statistics were then calculated from the resultant \ndata. \nThe Carpenter Hill Export (CARPEX), North-East New England Import (NENE), and Southeast Massachusetts + South Boston \nImport (SEMASB) interfaces were activated on February 7, hour ending 15. The Barnstable Export (BARNEX) interface was \nactivated on September 12, hour ending 15. The Southeast Massachusetts/Rhode Island - New England (SEMARI) and New \nEngland- SEMA/RI (SEMRII) interfaces were retired on September 12, hour ending 15. \nFlow and limit data are reported in the direction denoted in the interface name. For instance, “MENH” models flows and \nlimits from Maine to New Hampshire. \nThese data represent the ISO’s best information as compiled in its internal systems, and are presented ‘as is’ for the user’s \ninformation, with no warranties expressed or implied. Actual system conditions weigh heavily on the data shown here, and \nlikely affect these data in a manner that is not fully expressed within the data. Limit data is as recorded in the ISO's system, \nand is not the same as Total Transfer Capability (TTC). \n\nMore Information For more information on the sub-regional hourly and 5-minute costs of congestion, visit the ISO-NE web site here, and download the Excel file ‘2023 Price-Responsive Demand (PRD) Aggregation Zone LMP Stats.xlsx’ Questions concerning these data should be directed to the ISO’s Information Contact at isoneinfocontact@iso-ne.com.\n\nThermal\n\nGROUP 1 Stability/ Voltage\n\n| BARNEX Barnstable Export | Yes |\n| --- | --- |\n| BH-EXP Bangor Hydro Export | Yes |\n| BH+KRE Bangor Hydro & Keene Rd Export | Yes |\n| BSTN New England - Boston | Yes |\n| CARPEX Carpenter Hill Export | Yes |\n| CT-EXP Connecticut Export | Yes |\n| CTIMP Connecticut Import | Yes |\n| DNEAST Down East Export | Yes |\n| HI-IMP Highgate Import | Yes |\n| IRMF-E Inner Rumford Export | Yes |\n| KR-EXP Keene Road Export | Yes |\n| LS-ERI Lower SEMA/Eastern RI Import | Yes Yes |\n| MENH Maine - New Hampshire | Yes Yes |\n| NB-NE New Brunswick - New England | Yes |\n| NE_EW New England East -West | Yes |\n| GROUP 2 | Stability/ Thermal Voltage |\n| NE_WE New England West -East | Yes Yes |\n| NENE North-East New England Import | Yes |\n| NENY New England – New York | Yes Yes |\n| NHME New Hampshire-Maine | Yes |\n| NHSC-I New Hampshire Seacoast Import | Yes |\n| NOSO North - South | Yes |\n| NRST New England - Norwalk Stamford | Yes |\n| NS_ST Northern New England Scobie 345kV - Scobie | + 394 Yes |\n| NWVT_I Northern Vermont Import | Yes |\n| OR-IMP Orrington Import | Yes |\n| ORMF-E Outer Rumford Export | Yes |\n\nGROUP 2 Stability/ Voltage\n\nThermal\n\nORR-NO Orrington - North Yes Yes ORR-SO Orrington - South Yes Yes\n\nGROUP 3 Stability/ Voltage Thermal\n\nRI-IMP Rhode Island Import Yes SBRK_S Seabrook - South Yes SEMARI Southeast Massachusetts/Rhode Island - New England Yes SEMASB Southeast Massachusetts + South Boston Import Yes SEMRII New England- SEMA/RI Yes SHFHGE Sheffield + Highgate Export Yes SURO-S Surowiec - South Yes SWCT New England - Southwest Connecticut Yes WESTCT Western Connecticut Import Yes WTS+GR Whitefld South + GRPW Yes WYM-EX Wyman Hydro Export Yes\n\nFile Contents: summary_stats_2023_hrly.xlsx Tabs: ‘interfacename’ Summaries of the hourly data by month, 2023\n\n| ‘interfacename’ | Summaries of the hourly data by month, 2023 |\n| --- | --- |\n| Column Name | Description |\n| mnth | Month |\n| avg_hrly_flow | The average hourly flow, in MW, on the interface for the month. Positive values denote consistency with the modeled direction; negative values denote flows in the opposite of defined direction. |\n| max_hrly_flow | The maximum hourly flow, in MW, recorded during the month. |\n| min_hrly_flow | The minimum hourly flow, in MW, recorded during the month. |\n| sd_hrly_flow | The standard deviation of the hourly flow, in MW, recorded during the month. |\n| unlim_hi_hrs | The number of hours during the month where the limit was essentially non-existent. |\n| counter_flow_hrs | The number of hours during the month when the flow went counter to the defined direction. |\n| count_hrly_limit | The number of valid limit values on the interface during the month. |\n| avg_hrly_limit | The average hourly limit on the interface during the month where the limit is valid. |\n| max_hrly_limit | The maximum valid limit on the interface during the month. |\n| min_hrly_limit | The minimum valid limit on the interface during the month. |\n\nFile Contents: hourly_flows_2023.xlsx \nTabs: ‘Group_n’ Hourly Flows and Limits, 2023 \nColumn Name Description \nday The day \nhour The hour ending \ninterfacename_act The hourly sampled flow value in MW. \ninterfacename_limit The hourly sampled limit value in MW. Null if invalid. \n\n",
