      "text": "Appendix C: System \nEfficiency Needs Scenario\n© ISO New England Inc.\nEconomic Studies Technical Guide\nREVISION: 1.0\nEFFECTIVE DATE: AUGUST 5, 2025\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nRevision 1.0 – Effective Date: 08/05/2025 page 2\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nDisclaimer\nThe provisions in this Economic Study Technical Guide (Guide) are intended to be consistent with \nISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff (Tariff). If any language in the Guide \nconflicts with the Tariff, the language in the Tariff takes precedence. Capitalized terms used but not \ndefined in this Guide have the meaning ascribed to them in the Tariff or the NERC Glossary of \nTerms.\nRevision 1.0 – Effective Date: 08/05/2025 page 3\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nOverview\nThe purpose of the System Efficiency Needs Scenario (SENS) is to identify elements of the Pool \nTransmission Facilities (PTF) portion of the New England transmission system that will experience \ncongestion above a dollar threshold and evaluate if the benefits of addressing the congestion \noutweigh costs in the ten-year planning horizon. When this occurs, the ISO will evaluate and \npossibly procure proposed competitive solutions to the efficiency issue.\nThe base SENS model estimates the production costs of the New England and surrounding \nNortheast Power Coordinating Council (NPCC) systems in the last year of the ten-year planning \nhorizon. Production cost models attempt to serve demand while minimizing production costs. The \nSENS models the New England transmission system in detail, allowing the ISO to identify which \ncongested elements would cause a deviation from the optimal minimum cost dispatch. The SENS \nalso models possible transmission upgrades to determine their production cost savings. \nData Sources\nThe ISO obtains transmission data for the New England portion of the SENS model from a variety of \nISO transmission planning data sources. Transmission topology comes from the most recent \nversion of the Transmission Planning Base Case Library (TPBCL). The TPBCL provides line and \ntransformer impedances and ratings, along with generator interconnection points and nodal \ndistributed generation and demand. The ISO obtains interface, and contingency definitions are \nfrom the Base Case Data Base (BCDB). The software tool Transmission Adequacy & Reliability \nAssessment (TARA) identifies the contingency monitored element or contingency pairs most likely \nto bind. \nInterregional interface limits and intraregional limits within NYISO are obtained from the NPCC \nLong Range Adequacy Overview (LRAO). External areas are modeled with zonal transmission detail. \nLoad, active demand response (ADR), behind the meter photovoltaic (BTM-PV), and resource \ndistributions for NYISO are taken from the most recent version of the NYISO Gold Book. All \ninterregional lines are modeled with a wheeling charge of $3/MWh for both directions to represent \ntrading friction or hurdle rates; these rates are intended to account for the scheduling rules and \nrestrictions that exist between balancing authorities. \nSection 4.1(f) of Attachment K to the ISO’s Open Access Transmission Tariff (OATT) describes\nwhich New England resources to include in the SENS, and the BCDB provides resource properties, \nwith internal data sources providing market sensitive data. The ISO uses the NERC Long Term \nReliability Assessment (LTRA) to determine which resources in the surrounding NPCC systems \nshould be included. Modeling includes all existing and tier 1 resources except those with a \nconfirmed retirement date before the modeled year. \nThe ISO obtains fuel prices for each region from the most recent US Energy Information \nAdministration (EIA) Annual Energy Outlook, and it assigns a projected regional greenhouse gas \ninitiative (RGGI) to all regional carbon dioxide emissions. The ISO obtains Fuel-based emission \nRevision 1.0 – Effective Date: 08/05/2025 page 4\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nrates for carbon dioxide emissions are obtained from EIA data. Carbon dioxide emission rates for \nsome fuels are derived from historical ISO data. \nA vendor-supplied natural gas availability tool generates daily pipeline gas and LNG allocations \nwithin New England, based on daily average temperatures. For NYISO, the ISO created a similar tool\nbased on a regression of historical pipeline flows, generator fuel consumptions, and temperatures, \nand a combination of the New England and New York tools creates data for joint NY-NE pipeline gas \nand LNG constraints.\nEnergy production profiles for New England and New York wind and PV resources are provided by a \nDNV Variable Energy Resources dataset. These profiles include an allowance for losses and \nvendor-assumed forced outages. Data for wind and PV in other areas are taken from National \nRenewable Energy Labs (NREL) profiles based on the wind speed and irradiance of the largest \nexisting wind and PV sites. The wind profiles are converted to energy production profiles via generic \nwind speed power curves and outage rates consistent with the DNV profiles. \nThe ISO models New England hydro generators with monthly energy allocations based on the last \nsix years of generation data. The ISO models all external regions besides HQ using energy \nallocations that are converted to monthly energy limits and assigned to external hydro generators. \nThe ISO models HQ hydro use a weather year-correlated energy budget. Given the capacity \nconstraints of hydro generators within Quebec, the budget of Quebec hydro is dispatched to \nminimize production cost. \nNew England generator properties used in the model include different types of market sensitive \ndata taken from ISO internal data sources. Market sensitive data associated with external \ngenerators are obtained using regressions based on resource type and size, e.g., the ISO uses a \nregression of all combined cycle nameplate versus combined cycle heat rate to represent all \nexternal combined cycle generators. \nData for units without market sensitive data rely on a generic threshold order: BTM-PV are assigned \na price of -$99/MWh, utility wind and PV units are assigned a price of -$10/MWh, hydro units are \nassigned a price of $0/MWh, and all ADRs are assigned a price of $500/MWh. \nThe model assumes both New England and external battery energy storage system (BESS) units rely \non Li-ion technology, and the ISO simulates these units with an 85% round-trip-efficiency (RTE) and \na $3/MWh VO&M charge. The ISO simulates pumped storage units with a 74% RTE and a $3/MWh \nvariable operations and maintenance (VO&M) charge. \nThe ISO load forecasting team provides load profiles for each New England load zone. The ISO \nobtains distributions mapping a load zone profile to individual nodes, represented by a static \npercentage based on annual peak loads, from the BCDB. The ISO generates load data for external \nregions using historical load profiles mapped onto NERC LTRA summer peak, winter peak, and \nannual demand energy forecasts using monthly scaling factors. \nRevision 1.0 – Effective Date: 08/05/2025 page 5\nISO-NE PUBLIC\nTwo Pass Modeling Methodology\nThe production cost model consists of two passes. The first pass of the model contains the full \nNPCC model but only enforces interregional transmission constraints. The purpose of this is to \ndiscern the maximum economic transfer between zones if no internal constraints were to exist. The \nborder locational marginal prices (LMPs) will also be extracted from this first model to determine \nthe hourly marginal resources for each zone. \nIn the second pass of the model, the interregional flows and LMPs from the first model replace the \nexternal NPCC representation. Internal New England constraints are enforced. The import profiles \nare priced at the LMP of the first pass. If an internal constraint reduces the amount of imported \nenergy, the benefit of relieving that import will be equal to the difference between the production \ncost of additional generation needed to serve demand and the price of the hourly external m",
